05138nam a22009255i 9780520957213DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209572137 a10.1525/97805209572132doi  a(DE-B1597)519740  a(OCoLC)865246148  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a781.5/942231 aCooley, Timothy J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSurfing about Music /cTimothy J. Cooley. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tList of Online Examples -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Trouble in Paradise: The History and Reinvention of Surfing -- t2. “Surf Music” and the California Surfing Boom: New Surfing Gets a New Sound -- t3. Music in Surf Movies -- t4. Two Festivals and Three Genres of Music -- t5. The Pro Surfer Sings -- t6. The Soul Surfer Sings -- t7. Playing Together and Solitary Play: Why Surfers Need Music -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tDiscography -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis first major examination the interrelationships of music and surfing explores different ways that surfers combine surfing with making and listening to music. Tim Cooley uses his knowledge and experience as a practicing musician and avid surfer to consider the musical practices of surfers in locations around the world, taking into account ideas about surfing as a global affinity group and the real-life stories of surfers and musicians he encounters. In doing so, he expands ethnomusicological thinking about the many ways musical practices are integral to human socializing, creativity, and the condition of being human. Cooley discusses the origins of surfing in Hawai‘i, its central role in Hawaiian society, and the mele (chants) and hula (dance or visual poetry) about surfing. He covers instrumental rock from groups like Dick Dale and the Del Tones and many others, and songs about surfing performed by the Beach Boys. As he traces trends globally, three broad styles emerge: surf music, punk rock, and acoustic singer-songwriter music. Cooley also examines surfing contests and music festivals as well as the music used in a selection surf movies that were particularly influential in shaping the musical practices of significant groups of surfers. Engaging, informative, and enlightening, this book is a fascinating exploration of surfing as a cultural practice with accompanying rituals, habits, and conceptions about who surfs and why, and of how musical ideas and practices are key to the many things that surfing is and aspires to be.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusicxSocial aspects. 0aSurf musicxHistory and criticism. 0aSurfingxHistory. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aamerica.  abeach boys.  acultural practices.  adel tones.  adick dale.  aethnomusicologists.  aethnomusicology.  agenre studies.  aglobal surfers.  ahawaiian society.  ahula.  ahuman socializing.  ainstrumental rock.  amele.  amusic and culture.  amusic festivals.  amusic genres.  amusic scholars.  amusic studies.  amusical practices.  amusicians.  apunk rock.  asinger songwriters.  asurf movies.  asurf music.  asurfers.  asurfing contests.  asurfing culture.  asurfing music.  asurfing origins.  asurfing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027664240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095721340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520957213423Coveruhttp